    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter May 1st with a lineup headlined by **Pete Crow-Armstrong**, who earns our highest efficiency score of 69.58. Despite a wind-in warning at the stadium, his +14% dynamic platoon edge against the opposing starter provides the necessary leverage to overcome the external conditions, making him our priority play for speed and Roto category production. Joining him at the top of the efficiency charts are **Yordan Alvarez** (63.92) and **Kazuma Okamoto** (63.91). While **Yordan Alvarez** faces a lefty-on-lefty disadvantage that depresses his ceiling slightly, his elite xwOBA of 0.436 guarantees he remains a cornerstone, while **Kazuma Okamoto** benefits from a soft 4.87 xERA matchup, allowing him to exploit the favorable pitching environment to drive in runs.\n\nStrategic benching remains a fluid process as we navigate the absence of **Trea Turner**, **Christian Yelich**, **Hyeseong Kim**, and **Colt Keith**. Among our active, available roster, **Caleb Durbin** (49.84) and **Jerar Encarnacion** (48.52) represent the bottom of our starting hierarchy. While **Caleb Durbin** typically projects for high stolen base utility, his placement in the #9 hole forces a significant -8% penalty to his score. Our most difficult decision revolved around **Dillon Dingler** (53.55); while his score is technically higher than that of **Jerar Encarnacion**, we are monitoring the -8% impact from the opponent\u2019s SP skill level. We remain cautious of **Pete Crow-Armstrong** despite his high score, as the \"Wind In\" warning could suppress power totals, though his contribution to the scarce stolen base category remains the primary factor in his inclusion. With **Gary Sanchez**, **Zac Veen**, **Luke Raley**, **Lars Nootbaar**, **Josh Smith**, **Luis Pena**, and **Pedro Ramirez** held in reserve, the Zebras are well-positioned to pivot should any late-inning weather alerts or lineup shifts necessitate a change.",
